.SH CONTEXT
.PP
The following contexts are of interest:
.\"
.SS STREAMS Synchronous
Running under
.I STREAMS
and synchronized against the target queue.  A Stream head plumbing lock is held in the Stream to
which the queue belongs, or the
.B STRWOPEN
bit is held.
.PP
This is the case when the Stream is frozen, or when executing a queue put or service procedure, open
or close call-out, or a synchronous callback for the target queue.
.I q_next
pointers can be dereferenced for any queue in the Stream without being invalidated.
.\"
.SS STREAMS Asynchronous
Running under
.I STREAMS
but not synchronized against the target queue.
.PP
This is the case when executing a synchronous procedure, call-out or callback, for a queue in one
Stream and referencing a queue in another Stream.  It is also the case when an asynchronous callback
(one not referenced on a queue) is being executed.
.PP
Under the special case when running under
.I STREAMS
where the target queue belongs to a Stream linked to a lower multiplex, the context can be
considered as synchronous if the caller can suppress concurrent unlinking of the Stream.  This can
normally be performed with private locks taken within a put or service procedure of a multiplexing
driver.  But this is complex and best avoided by treating all such queues as asynchronous.
.\"
.SS Non-STREAMS Asynchronous
Not running under
.I STREAMS
and not synchronized against the target queue.
.PP
This is the case when calling any utility from outside of
.IR STREAMS .
This can be from process context, software interrupt, bottom-halves, tasklets,
.B Linux
timeouts, interrupt service routines, etc.
.PP
.RI Non- STREAMS
asynchronous contexts can be synchronized against a queue with
.BR freezestr (9),
.BR qwriter (9),
.BR streams_put (9),
.\"
.SS Validity and Exclusion
.PP
In a synchronous context, all
.I q_next
pointer dereferences for any queue in the Stream to which the synchronization queue belongs is
valid for the duration of the context.
In an asynchronous context, no assurances of the validity of
.I q_next
dereferences can be made.   This is of primary concern to
.I STREAMS
utilities that dereference a
.I q_next
pointer.
As discussed briefly above, lower multiplex Streams are of less concern that upper multiplex Streams
(that could be closed or have modules pushed or popped at any time).
.PP
When in a synchronous context with respect to a queue, a plumbing read lock is held for the Stream
head of the Stream to which the queue belongs.  Utilities that deference
.I q_next
without first taking a Stream head plumbing read lock can only be called in a synchronous context.
Utilities that acquire a Stream head plumbing read lock before dereferencing
.I q_next
can be called from any context, but would be wasteful and scale poorly if normally called from
synchronous context.
Utilities that do not dereference
.I q_next
and only affect the queue itself, take a queue write lock and can be called from any
context.
.PP
.B Validity/Exclusion for q
.PP
All
.I STREAMS
utilities that accept a queue pointer require validity of the queue pointer across the call, but not
exclusion: exclusion is accomplished within the utility with locks.
.PP
When in the synchronous context, any queue in the Stream can be passed to a utility function and it
is guaranteed valid.  However, in the asynchronous context, the caller is responsible for ensuring
the validity of the passed in queue pointer.  A pointer to a queue remains valid from the point that
the
.IR qi_qopen (9)
routine for a queue pair is entered, until just before the
.IR qi_qopen (9)
routine for the queue pair is exited.
Therefore, references to a queue that are acquired in the
.IR qi_qopen (9)
routine and released in the
.IR qi_qclose (9)
routine are guaranteed valid.
.PP
For example, an interrupt service routine that is established and passed a read queue pointer on
.IR qi_qopen (9)
for the queue pair, and if the ISR is disabled in the
.IR qi_qclose (9)
for the queue pair, releasing the read queue pointer,
then the read queue pointer is valid to be used in any
.I STREAMS
utility called during the ISR.
.PP
Pointers to queues in a Stream that is linked to a lower multiplex are guaranteed valid while the
Stream remains linked (the
.IR qi_qclose (9)
routine cannot be called until it is unlinked).  This is also true for
.I q_next
pointers, in that modules cannot be pushed or popped from a Stream linked to a lower multiplex until
it is unlinked.
Therefore, if a multiplexing driver can guarantee, by acquiring a private lock, that no Stream will
be unlinked until the lock is released, a pointer to any queue in any lower multiplex Stream will be
guaranteed valid, and the context can be considered synchronous for any Stream on the lower
multiplex.
Pointers to queues in an upper multiplex cannot be guaranteed in this way (because modules can be
pushed or popped from an asynchronous Stream at any time).
.PP
.I STREAMS
utilities that require exclusive access to the referenced queue, take their own write locks on the
queue.  Therefore, the caller does not have to ensure exclusion on the
.BR queue (9)
structure or any attached [e.g.,
.BR qband (9)]
structures.
.PP
.B Validity/Exclusion for mp
.PP
All
.I STREAMS
utilities that accept a message pointer require both validity of the message pointer across the
call, exclusion on the message block across the call, and exclusion on the data block or buffer of
the message altered by the utility across the call.
.PP
When in a synchronous context and the message has been passed to the queue's put procedure, removed
from the the queue by its service procedure, or freshly allocated (regardless of context), the
message pointer is guaranteed valid until passed to another put procedure.
.PP
Whenever a dereference of a message pointer is valid, the holder of the dereference has exclusive
access to the
.BR msgb (9)
message block structure.
If the
.BR datab (9)
data block structure has a reference count
.I db_ref
of one, the holder also has exclusive access to the data block.  If the holder has exclusive access
to the data block and there is no extended buffer attached to the data block (i.e., it was allocated
with
.BR allocb (9)
and not
.BR esballoc (9),
the holder also has exclusive access to the data buffer.
When
.I db_ref
is greater than 1, the easiest way to obtain exclusion from the data block and data buffer is to
copy the data block using utilities such as
.BR copyb (9)
or
.BR copymsg (9). 
.\"
.SS "Stream Ends and Multiplexing"
.PP
Passing of messages along a Stream using
.I q_next
pointers and the
.RI \(lq next \(rq
versions of the
.I STREAMS
utilities
.RB ( putnext (9),
.BR canputnext (9),
.BR bcanputnext (9),
.BR qreply (9))
is simple and straightforward.  These functions are always invoked from within one of queue pair's
procedures, and Stream synchronization is performed before entering the procedure within which they
are called.  These are
.I STREAMS
synchronous contexts.
.PP
.IR "Stream ends" ,
(Stream head, Driver, Upper Multiplexer, Lower Multiplexer), on the other hand are more problematic
because they interface with contexts within which Stream synchronization has not been performed.
These are asynchronous contexts and are more problematic.
.PP
A Stream end exists at the queue pair forming the Stream head, Driver, or Upper or Lower Multiplexer;
each is separately discussed:
.PP
Interaction between user process context and the Stream head is performed by the
specialized functions of the Stream head.  Modules and drivers do not normally need to provide any
of these procedures.
.\"
.SS Driver Read Queue
.PP
For the driver read queue there are two approaches as well.  Again, the first is not problematic,
the second is.
.PP
.B Approach #1.
.PP
Under the first approach, the driver read queue has both a put and a service procedure.
For driver read queues with service procedures, the non-MP approach used to be not even define a put
procedure, but to place messages directly on the read queue, using
.BR putq (9).
All actions would then be taken out of the driver read queue's service procedure.
Some variations, however, would use
.BR canputnext (9)
or
.BR bcanputnext (9)
when determining whether to use
.BR putq (9)
or
.BR putnext (9).
.PP
The pure
.BR putq (9)
variation is still a viable approach for
.BR "@PACKAGE_TITLE@" .
.BR putq (9)
does not dereference any
.I q_next
pointer, and takes the queue write locks necessary to protect the queue structure both inside and
outside of
.IR STREAMS .
A more portable MP approach is to provide a put procedure that simply does a
.BR putq (9)
and use the
.BR put (9)
call to invoke it.
.PP
Calling
.BR canputnext (9)
or
.BR bcanputnext (9)
however, does dereference a
.I q_next
pointer and are not MP-safe from an asynchronous context.
Drivers using these variations must define a put procedure and invoke it with
.BR put (9)
to enter a
.I STREAMS
synchronous context (the put procedure), before calling any of the
.RI \(lq next \(rq
versions of functions such as
.BR putnext (9),
.BR canputnext (9),
or
.BR bcanputnext (9).
.PP
If an ISR feeding a driver read queue with a service procedure needs to determine whether the queue
is full for a given band,
before calling
.BR put (9),
the ISR or bottom half can call
.BR canput (9)
or
.BR bcanput (9)
from outside of
.I STREAMS
synchronization. Under all implementation this seems acceptable as long as the driver read queue has
a service procedure (otherwise, these functions might try to scan upstream for a queue with a
service procedure, dereferencing
.I q_next
pointers along the way).
.PP
.B Approach #2.
.PP
The second approach defines a put procedure but no service procedure for the driver read queue.  The 
classical non-MP approach was to either call the put procedure directly using the
.I qi_putp
function pointer, or to not define a put procedure and make calls to
.BR putnext (9)
directly from the ISR or bottom half.
This approach cannot work on MP.
.BR putnext (9)
cannot be called from outside
.I STREAMS
synchronous context.
.PP
For MP, the proper technique is to define a put procedure and use
.BR put (9)
to invoke it.  Once within the put procedure,
.BR putnext (9)
can be called safely.
.PP
.B Summary.
.PP
All implementations of
.I STREAMS
use
.BR put (9)
to enter a
.I STREAMS
synchronous context and invoke the put procedure for the specified queue.  All driver read qeues
must define a put procedure, and
.BR put (9)
is the only way that messages should be passed to the queue from outside of
.IR STREAMS .
Driver must be aware, however, that the put procedure of the driver read queue might not be directly
invoked as a function call, but might be deferred for later execution in a different context.
On the other hand, when invoke directly from an ISR, the put procedure might run in ISR context.
Whether the driver read queue has a service procedure or not is according to its own design,
however, it is more portable to provide one and never call
.BR putnext (9)
from the driver read queue put procedure, only the service procedure.  This is because calling
.BR putnext (9)
will invoke the upstream module's put procedure in ISR context and on the ISR stack.  The upstream
module might not be prepared for this.
.\"
.SS Driver Write Queue.
.PP
The driver write queue can be implemented in one of two ways.  The first is not problematic.  The
second is.
.PP
.B Method #1.
.PP
In the first method, the driver write queue has both a put and a service procedure.  The put
procedure responds to critical or immediate messages and places all data messages onto the message
queue.  The service procedure removes messages from the message queue and outputs them to the hardware.
If there is too much data for the hardware to accept, the service procedure places the message back
on the queue and returns.  When a hardware interrupt makes it possible for the service procedure to
again write data, the transmit ISR enables the write queue by calling
.BR enableq (9)
or
.BR qenable (9).
.PP
A similar approach can be taken if the driver is a pseudo-device (software) driver rather than a
hardware device driver.  Instead of outputing to the hardware, the service procedure takes the data
from messages and passes in some manner to the external subsystem.
.PP
This first method is quite portable.
.PP
.B Method #2.
.PP
In the second method, the driver write queue has only a put procedure.  The put procedure responds
to critical or immediate messages and places all data messages onto the message queue.  The transmit
ISR (or a bottom half of the transmit ISR) directly performs the functions performed by the service
procedure in the first method above.
.PP
The routine uses
.BR rmvq (9),
.BR getq (9),
.BR flushq (9),
.BR flushband (9),
and
.BR appq (9),
.BR insq (9),
.BR putq (9),
.BR putbq (9),
in the same fashion as a service procedure would.  Under
.BR "@PACKAGE_TITLE@" ,
.BR rmvq (9),
.BR getq (9),
.BR flushq (9),
.BR flushband (9),
are safe to be called asynchronously on a Stream end.  The difference with this approach, however,
is that the method is only applicable to MP-safe drivers, because synchronization with the framework
is not peformed for an interrupt service routine.
.PP
This method relies on
.BR canputnext (9)
and
.BR bcanputnext (9)
setting the
.BR QWANTW
and
.BR QB_WANTW
bits on the driver write queue even though it does not have a service procedure.  This is provided
for under
.IR "SVR 4 STREAMS" .
.[
svr4spg
.]
.BR canputnext (9)
and
.BR bcanputnext (9)
will operate on a queue that has no next queue regardless of whether it has a service procedure or
not.
.PP
This second method is not as portable
.IR "to other implementations" .
.PP
.B Summary.
.PP
Because the first method, for all intents and purposes, should perform just as well as the second
method, it is recommended that portable
.I STREAMS
drivers and modules only use the first method for driver write queues.  Under the first method, only
.BR enableq (9)
or
.BR qenable (9)
are called from outside of the
.I STREAMS
synchronous context, and the interface between Stream and ISR is simple.
.\"
.SS Upper Multiplexer Read Queue
.PP
Passing messages between upper multiplexer Streams, or from a lower multiplexer Stream to an upper
on is problematic, because the procedure passing the message is not in a synchronous context with
respect to the Stream to which messages are being passed.  Each upper multiplexer Stream, when used
in this fashion, should be treated like the driver read queue described above.  That is, each upper
multiplexer Stream must have a read queue put procedure, and that procedure must be invoked using
.BR put (9).
.BR canput (9)
and
.BR bcanput (9)
can be used on any upper multiplexer Stream read queue provided that the caller can ensure that the
passed in queue pointer will remain valid across the call (e.g, the Stream will not close).
.\"
.SS Upper Multiplexer Write Queue
.PP
The upper multiplexer write queue should follow the procedures and recommendations decribed for the
driver write queue.  The upper multiplexer write queue can be implemented with or without a service
procedure.
.\"
.SS Lower Multiplexer Write Queue
.PP
.\"
.SS Lower Multiplexer Read Queue
.PP
The lower multiplexer read queue should follow the procedures and recommendations decribed for the
driver write queue, except in an upside-down sense.  The lower multiplexer read queue can be
implemented with or without a service procedure.
.PP
.\"
