.SS Plumbing
.PP
Most plumbing operations performed on a Stream are performed from user process context (i.e., in
response to a system call).
One exception is
.BR welq (9)
and
.BR unweldq (9)
if they were to be called from a
.IR qi_putp (9)
procedure instead of a
.IR qi_qopen (9)
or
.IR qi_qclose (9)
routine.
.PP
Plumbing operations include
.BR open (2s),
.BR close (2s),
.BR I_POP (7),
.BR I_PUSH (7),
.BR weldq (9),
.BR unweldq (9).
So, generally, any operation that invokes
.IR qi_qopen (9)
or
.IR qi_qclose (9)
to create or destroy the queue pair instance of a driver or module in a Stream, plus any welding of
Streams.
.BR I_LINK (7),
.BR I_UNLINK (7),
.BR I_PLINK (7),
.BR I_PUNLINK (7),
are not plumbing operations in the sense that they do not alter
.I q_next
pointers.
.PP
.B "@PACKAGE_TITLE@"
.[
@PACKAGE_TITLE@
.]
provides a specialized plumbing reader-writer lock in the Stream head to protect the
.I q_next
pointers (i.e., the plumbing) in a Stream.  When the plumbing reader-writer lock is acquired for
read, any
.I q_next
pointer in the entire Stream can be dereferenced and the dereference will remain valid until the
lock is released.
The reader-writer lock is acquired for write by any plumbing operation, as was described above.
.PP
All queue procedures, call-outs, and synchronous callbacks associated are synchronized against a
queue that belongs to a Stream which has a Stream head.  Before the synchronous procedure, call-out
or callback is invoked, the
.I STREAMS
scheduler thread acquires the Stream head (associated with the synchronizing queue) plumbing
reader-writer lock for read.  This means that any queue procedure, call-out, and callback,
synchronized on a queue, can dereference any
.I q_next
pointer within the Stream to which the synchronizing queue belongs, without any special treatment.
.PP
Some other implementations (e.g.,
.IR HP-UX \(rg,
.[
hpuxspg
.]
place restrictions upon which queue pointers can be passed to which utility functions and which
utility functions can be called from within the
.I STREAMS
framework and which can be called from outside the
.I STREAMS
framework.
.PP
.B "@PACKAGE_TITLE@"
does not place such restrictions on most
.I STREAMS
utilities.  The only
.I STREAMS
utilities that are restricted are
.BR qprocson (9),
and
.BR qprocsoff (9),
which must be called from a
.IR qi_qopen (9)
open, or
.IR qi_qclose (9)
close routine for a driver or module.
The remaining utilities can be called from outside of
.I STREAMS
provided that the caller can ensure the validity of any passed in queue pointer,
.IR q ,
and exclusive access to any passed in message,
.IR mp .
.PP
The validity of a passed in queue pointer, or its
.I q_next
pointer is guaranteed by
.B "@PACKAGE_TITLE@"
whenever it (or its pair) was passed to a module procedure, callout, or synchronous callback.
Asynchronous callbacks passed
.I q
