.SS Freezing
.PP
In the Uni-Processor (UP) environment, it was sufficient to raise the system priority level
to ensure that no other queue procedures or thread were accessing the
Stream.
This was performed with
.BR splstr (9)
and
.BR splx (9).
.PP
In the Symmetric Multi-Processor (SMP) environment, it is also necessary to hold a lock to block
other processors from entering the critical section.
This is achieved by freezing the
Stream
with
.BR freezestr (9)
and thawing it with
.BR unfreezestr (9).
.RS
.ll -7n
.PP
.B Note:
when
.BR freezestr (9)
is called in a Uni-Processor (UP) environment, it is equivalent to
.BR splstr (9);
.BR unfreezestr (9),
.BR splx (9).
.ll +7n
.RE
.PP
Freezing a Stream results in local interrupts being suppressed and the Stream head reader-writer
freeze lock being held for write.  The Stream head reader-writer plumbing lock is also acquired for
read.  Thawing a Stream releases the read and write locks and restores local interrupts.
.PP
The Stream head plumbing reader-writer lock is acquired for write by any plumbing operation on the
Stream that would change
.I q_next
pointers on either queue pair.
Holding the Stream head plumbing read lock blocks any plumbing changes to the Stream.
.PP
The Stream head freeze reader-writer lock is acquired for read by any thread other than
the freezing thread entering a queue procedure
.RI [ qi_putp "(9) or " qi_srvp (9)].
After being acquired, the read lock is immediately released.  This stops any queue procedure from
being entered after the Stream is frozen by any thread other than the thread that froze the Stream,
but allows threads already executing in a queue procedure to proceed.  This is in accordance with
the descriptions for
.BR freezestr (9).
.PP
Many other implementations require that a Stream (and queue) be frozen by the caller with
.BR freezestr (9),
across a call to
.BR appq (9),
.BR insq (9),
.BR rmvq (9),
.BR strqget (9),
.BR strqset (9),
and require that a Stream (and queue)
.B not
be frozen by the caller with
.BR freezestr (9),
across a call to
.BR putq (9),
.BR putbq (9),
.BR getq (9),
.BR put (9),
.BR putnext (9),
.BR canput (9),
.BR canputnext (9),
.BR bcanput (9),
.BR bcanputnext (9),
and a host of others.
The precise functions vary from implementation to implementation.  See
.BR freezestr (9)
for more information.
.PP
.B "@PACKAGE_TITLE@"
permits all queue functions other than
.BR qprocson (9),
.BR qprocsoff (9),
.BR freezestr (9),
to be called on a Stream frozen by the caller.
.B "@PACKAGE_TITLE@"
also permits
.BR appq (9),
.BR insq (9),
.BR rmvq (9),
.BR strqget (9),
.BR strqset (9),
to be called on a thawed Stream provided that the caller provides some other mutual exclusion to
guarantee the validity of any arguments that reference a message on the queue.
For example, a driver's read queue can only have messages placed on the queue and taken off of the
the queue by a driver procedure.  With driver-private locks, it is possible to ensure that at a
given point in time the queue state is frozen even though the Stream is thawed.
.PP
.B "@PACKAGE_TITLE@"
provides maximum portability and compatibility in this regard.
.\"
.\"
.SS Queue Pointers
.PP
In the Uni-Processor (UP) environment, calling
.BR splstr (9)
is sufficient to ensure that a valid queue pointer
.I q
will not invalidate across a call to any function until
.BR splx (9)
was called.  This is not the case in the Symmetric Multi-Processor (SMP) environment.
.PP
In the SMP environment, another processor may be executing
.IR qi_putp (9)
or
.IR qi_srvp (9)
procedures, or synchronous callbacks, concurrent with
.IR qi_qopen (9)
or
.IR qi_qclose (9)
procedures.
Utilities called from the
.RI non- STREAMS
context (process context, asynchronous callbacks, soft interrupts, and interrupt service routines)
can execute concurrent with any procedures within the
.I STREAMS
environment
.RI ( qi_qopen (9),
.IR qi_qclose (9),
.IR qi_putp (9),
.IR qi_srvp (9),
synchronous callbacks, buffer free routines).
.IR qi_qopen (9)
and
.IR qi_qclose (9)
procedures, in particular, can cause
.I q_next
pointers to change, and
.IR qi_qclose (9)
procedures can also result in the deallocation of queues.
The only
.I STREAMS
utilities that are provided that permit blocking of plumbing changes to the
Stream
are
.BR freezestr "(9), " unfreezestr (9)
and
.BR MPSTR_STPLOCK "(9), " MPSTR_STPRELE (9)
(from the
.BR uw7compat (5)
module in the
.I STREAMS Compatibility Modules
.BR strcompat (5)
package.)
.\"
.\"
.SS Message Pointers
.PP
In both the UP and SMP environments, it is the responsibility of the caller to ensure exclusive
access to any message pointer
.I mp
passed to any message handling or queue handing function.  Exclusive access does not have to be
ensured to the data blocks associated with the messages, and in particular the
.I db_ref
member.
.\"
.\"
.SS Locking
.PP
Following is a discussion of the locking used in
.BR "@PACKAGE_TITLE@" :
.PP
.B @PACKAGE_TITLE@
performs reference counting on all
